 content parameter, and uses a regex pattern to strip out script tags while preserving the rest of the HTML. I'll return the result as JSON for consistency. filtered content directly as plain text, since that's what the task explicitly requests. The regex pattern removes script tags and their contents using `re.DOTALL` and `re.IGNORECASE` flags to handle multiline scripts and case variations. The endpoint accepts the content parameter via GET or POST, returning a 400 error if it's missing. tag with any attributes, then captures everything between the opening and closing tags non-greedily, and finally matches the closing tag. The `re.DOTALL` flag ensures the pattern works across multiple lines, while `re.IGNORECASE` handles variations like `<SCRIPT>` in uppercase. I'll write this solution to the file now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4644,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4644},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bf7af1b3-4e19-4b2e-99ff-7be2e38c9873","uuid":"4575faa9-99a3-4019-b484-7c793eff4eb7","request_id":"req_011CbdL7TSESYoyiLHMXgDGG"}
